00:02:02.350 --> 00:02:04.850
- I was bussed to
very white schools.

00:02:04.850 --> 00:02:06.850
I always knew I was not
going to put my daughter

00:02:06.850 --> 00:02:08.139
in that environment.

00:02:08.139 --> 00:02:09.729
I did not expect I
would also put her

00:02:09.729 --> 00:02:11.354
in a segregated environment.

00:02:20.066 --> 00:02:22.450
How do your friends
get to school?

00:02:22.450 --> 00:02:25.532
Dante lives across the
street, doesn't he?

00:02:25.532 --> 00:02:26.954
Where's Dante?

00:02:26.954 --> 00:02:30.240
- [INAUDIBLE] lives
across the street.

00:02:30.240 --> 00:02:32.430
- Oh, Jacoby rides the bus.

00:02:32.430 --> 00:02:33.575
- Morning, Najya.

00:02:33.575 --> 00:02:35.645
- Was Sam cranky this morning?

00:02:35.645 --> 00:02:38.880
- Um, he was OK.

00:02:38.880 --> 00:02:40.156
- [INAUDIBLE].

00:02:46.610 --> 00:02:50.170
- I don't talk to her about
that we intentionally chose

00:02:50.170 --> 00:02:51.770
the segregated school for her.

00:02:51.770 --> 00:02:52.960
I don't want her to notice.

00:02:52.960 --> 00:02:54.770
It was not an easy decision.

00:02:54.770 --> 00:02:58.220
I've spent my career chronicling
the way the segregated schools

00:02:58.220 --> 00:02:59.360
harm black children.

00:02:59.360 --> 00:03:03.950
But at the same time, this is
what public education to me is.

00:03:03.950 --> 00:03:06.479
This is the one place
where the masses can mix.

00:03:06.479 --> 00:03:08.020
This is the one
place where we're not

00:03:08.020 --> 00:03:09.950
supposed to all going
into our own corners

00:03:09.950 --> 00:03:12.093
with people who are
exactly like us.

00:03:17.517 --> 00:03:19.850
My daughter doesn't know that
there's a class difference

00:03:19.850 --> 00:03:21.260
between her and her classmates.

00:03:21.260 --> 00:03:23.210
She will as she gets
older, I'm sure.

00:03:23.210 --> 00:03:25.441
But right now, these
are just her friends.

00:03:25.441 --> 00:03:27.440
And I think that that's
the most important thing

00:03:27.440 --> 00:03:29.870
that I can give her
while also trying

00:03:29.870 --> 00:03:32.300
to even the playing
field a bit for the kids

00:03:32.300 --> 00:03:35.220
in the school whose parents
work hard every day,

00:03:35.220 --> 00:03:37.807
but they work jobs that
they don't have status.

00:03:37.807 --> 00:03:39.140
They don't have access to power.

00:03:39.140 --> 00:03:42.110
They can't write a 10,000-word
piece in the "New York Times

00:03:42.110 --> 00:03:43.590
Magazine" about
their experience.

00:03:43.590 --> 00:03:44.930
But I can do that.

00:03:44.930 --> 00:03:48.380
And my presence in the
school changes the status

00:03:48.380 --> 00:03:49.760
for those children too.

00:03:49.760 --> 00:03:51.260
I hoped, I think,
like many parents,

00:03:51.260 --> 00:03:53.720
that I would be able to
put her in an integrated--

00:03:53.720 --> 00:03:55.220
truly integrated
school environment.

00:03:55.220 --> 00:03:57.560
But in New York
City, your choices

00:03:57.560 --> 00:04:00.565
are often polar opposites.

00:04:00.565 --> 00:04:04.880
If those of us who have choice
and privilege and some power

00:04:04.880 --> 00:04:06.680
keep avoiding
schools, then we have

00:04:06.680 --> 00:04:10.470
accepted that this two-tiered
system is inevitable,

00:04:10.470 --> 00:04:11.470
and I don't accept that.

