00:54:52.040 --> 00:54:54.580
So that was-- and
they were worried, oh,

00:54:54.580 --> 00:54:58.180
there's another neighborhood
next to us that is not--

00:54:58.180 --> 00:55:01.750
that their kids aren't
that's studious.

00:55:01.750 --> 00:55:03.340
So I said, what's
the problem then?

00:55:03.340 --> 00:55:06.370
Oh, then the whole
classroom changes.

00:55:06.370 --> 00:55:10.087
Because right now, all of
them are more studious,

00:55:10.087 --> 00:55:11.920
and then in the middle
school, the classroom

00:55:11.920 --> 00:55:14.260
is, like, a mix of
from this neighborhood

00:55:14.260 --> 00:55:15.195
and that neighborhood.

00:55:15.195 --> 00:55:16.389
So then I said, so?

00:55:16.389 --> 00:55:17.180
What's the problem?

00:55:17.180 --> 00:55:18.730
Oh, they are not
studious enough.

00:55:18.730 --> 00:55:21.145
They don't, like, value
education that much.

00:55:21.145 --> 00:55:24.850
So I said, but is that
due to that neighborhood?

00:55:24.850 --> 00:55:28.284
Or is that just that
you expect that that has

00:55:28.284 --> 00:55:29.450
been happening historically?

00:55:29.450 --> 00:55:31.390
So what advice would
you give that, hey, it's

00:55:31.390 --> 00:55:35.010
actually better for your
children to be in such a school

00:55:35.010 --> 00:55:36.985
where it's more of a balance?

00:55:36.985 --> 00:55:40.360
And you can go and
change them rather than

00:55:40.360 --> 00:55:41.750
be worried about
getting changed,

00:55:41.750 --> 00:55:42.959
or whatever you think is bad?

00:55:42.959 --> 00:55:45.333
NIKOLE HANNAH-JONES: I mean,
I think you know the answer.

00:55:45.333 --> 00:55:46.000
[LAUGHTER]

00:55:46.000 --> 00:55:47.950
I mean, it's a real concern.

00:55:47.950 --> 00:55:50.980
I don't want to
downplay the concern.

00:55:50.980 --> 00:55:53.560
We all want our children
to get a quality education.

00:55:53.560 --> 00:55:58.480
We don't want our children to
be harmed by our decisions.

00:55:58.480 --> 00:56:02.500
What the data shows
is that white kids--

00:56:02.500 --> 00:56:05.260
and I don't know what
race your friends are--

00:56:05.260 --> 00:56:08.206
but Asian American kids,
unless they're coming--

00:56:08.206 --> 00:56:11.890
Asian American kids, if
they're coming as refugees,

00:56:11.890 --> 00:56:13.540
their test scores
and their experience

00:56:13.540 --> 00:56:16.081
actually very much mirrors that
of black and Latino students.

00:56:16.081 --> 00:56:18.430
But the majority of Asians
in this country are coming--

00:56:18.430 --> 00:56:23.500
their parents are coming on an
education visa or a work visa,

00:56:23.500 --> 00:56:26.380
or they're already second
or third generation.

00:56:26.380 --> 00:56:28.240
The data shows that
their test scores--

00:56:28.240 --> 00:56:32.200
if test scores are the
measure, don't go down.

00:56:32.200 --> 00:56:34.750
And that actually,
integration is

00:56:34.750 --> 00:56:39.890
great for our ability to think
things, to problem solve.

00:56:39.890 --> 00:56:43.210
Because as you know, if you're
working with a group of people

00:56:43.210 --> 00:56:45.280
where everyone thinks
the same, then you're

00:56:45.280 --> 00:56:47.405
all thinking the same way
of how to solve problems.

00:56:47.405 --> 00:56:50.830
And it's actually that
diversity that makes us smarter.

00:56:50.830 --> 00:56:53.020
I think fear is a hard
thing to overcome.

00:56:53.020 --> 00:56:55.390
But I think parents
need to understand,

00:56:55.390 --> 00:56:58.330
one, a lot of how well
your kids are going to do,

00:56:58.330 --> 00:57:00.730
if you're privileged,
is in the home.

00:57:00.730 --> 00:57:02.817
For lower income people,
they're much more

00:57:02.817 --> 00:57:04.900
dependent on what's going
to happen in the schools

00:57:04.900 --> 00:57:05.890
than in the home.

00:57:05.890 --> 00:57:08.020
And your kids are
going to be fine.

00:57:08.020 --> 00:57:11.010
I don't want my child
in a bubble, right?

00:57:11.010 --> 00:57:12.640
Like, I don't live
in a neighborhood.

00:57:12.640 --> 00:57:16.240
I could afford to live
in a neighborhood that's

00:57:16.240 --> 00:57:17.530
not low-income.

00:57:17.530 --> 00:57:20.290
But this is the real
world, and my child's

00:57:20.290 --> 00:57:22.510
not better than her
low-income neighbors.

00:57:22.510 --> 00:57:24.540
And they have a lot to offer.

00:57:24.540 --> 00:57:28.570
And I was a kid who was
bussed to white schools.

00:57:28.570 --> 00:57:32.440
And sometimes my parents
made so little money

00:57:32.440 --> 00:57:34.450
that we were on free
or reduced lunch.

00:57:34.450 --> 00:57:37.950
I was not dumber than those
kids because I was poor.

00:57:37.950 --> 00:57:40.870
And when people
say that families

00:57:40.870 --> 00:57:43.480
don't value an
education, I have never

00:57:43.480 --> 00:57:45.490
met a family who did
not want their kids

00:57:45.490 --> 00:57:46.930
to get a good education.

00:57:46.930 --> 00:57:48.920
They may not speak
the same language.

00:57:48.920 --> 00:57:52.720
They may not talk about it
in these, like, high terms

00:57:52.720 --> 00:57:54.160
that we talk about it in.

00:57:54.160 --> 00:57:56.680
But I've never met a
family who didn't want it,

00:57:56.680 --> 00:57:59.004
and I've never met a kid
who didn't want an education

00:57:59.004 --> 00:58:00.670
until they'd been in
schools long enough

00:58:00.670 --> 00:58:03.250
that show them that we don't
care about their education.

00:58:03.250 --> 00:58:08.684
So I think-- what I would
say is, you have to--

00:58:08.684 --> 00:58:10.600
if you don't believe in
the common good, fine.

00:58:10.600 --> 00:58:11.984
Right?

00:58:11.984 --> 00:58:13.150
I'm saying, let's be honest.

00:58:13.150 --> 00:58:14.370
You either do or you don't.

00:58:14.370 --> 00:58:17.170
But if you do, then it's OK to
go into those kids at schools.

00:58:17.170 --> 00:58:20.170
And if you have a good
teacher, teachers who are good

00:58:20.170 --> 00:58:21.910
know how to differentiate
instruction.

00:58:21.910 --> 00:58:23.140
That's how my
daughter's school is.

00:58:23.140 --> 00:58:24.500
There's some kids who
are more advanced--

00:58:24.500 --> 00:58:25.670
and I remember this
when I was a kid.

00:58:25.670 --> 00:58:27.440
We had, like, lions,
tigers, and bears,

00:58:27.440 --> 00:58:29.110
and there were three groups.

00:58:29.110 --> 00:58:34.180
And they were grouped based
on how advanced they were,

00:58:34.180 --> 00:58:36.450
and then the teacher would
spend time with each group

00:58:36.450 --> 00:58:38.450
during the day, providing
different instruction.

00:58:38.450 --> 00:58:40.575
And then most of the day,
we'd spend time together.

00:58:40.575 --> 00:58:42.790
Those are the things
that you're looking for.

00:58:42.790 --> 00:58:44.980
But I don't think I
can ever, you know,

00:58:44.980 --> 00:58:47.200
calm the fears of a
parent who's like, I

00:58:47.200 --> 00:58:49.210
know if I put my
kid in this school

00:58:49.210 --> 00:58:51.160
where every kid is
high achieving--

00:58:51.160 --> 00:58:54.550
and that seems very attractive.

00:58:54.550 --> 00:58:56.770
But I think that test
scores are actually

00:58:56.770 --> 00:58:58.720
a pretty terrible
measure, and I think

00:58:58.720 --> 00:59:00.930
we need to stop
believing that kids

00:59:00.930 --> 00:59:02.560
who are struggling
a little bit are not

00:59:02.560 --> 00:59:05.100
as valuable and as capable.

00:59:05.100 --> 00:59:06.850
Ooh, that was, like,
a five-minute answer.

00:59:06.850 --> 00:59:09.391
No, you're-- actually, you had
a long preamble, so that was--

00:59:09.391 --> 00:59:10.472
[LAUGHTER]

00:59:10.472 --> 00:59:12.430
SHEETHAL SHOBAWALE: Long
question, long answer.

00:59:12.430 --> 00:59:12.930
OK.

00:59:12.930 --> 00:59:13.910
How about last one?

00:59:13.910 --> 00:59:15.565
This is where-- we're overtime.

00:59:15.565 --> 00:59:16.720
AUDIENCE: I was wondering
what your thoughts are

00:59:16.720 --> 00:59:17.950
about magnet schools.

00:59:17.950 --> 00:59:21.880
I went to a magnet program in
a school in the suburbs of DC

00:59:21.880 --> 00:59:23.860
that was very diverse.

00:59:23.860 --> 00:59:28.010
To use your phrase, a UN
model nation kind of a thing.

00:59:28.010 --> 00:59:30.070
Admittedly, the classes
within the magnet program

00:59:30.070 --> 00:59:32.370
weren't nearly as diverse, but
the school itself as a whole

00:59:32.370 --> 00:59:32.660
was.

00:59:32.660 --> 00:59:34.410
So what do you think
about magnet programs

00:59:34.410 --> 00:59:35.630
as a potential solution?

00:59:35.630 --> 00:59:37.820
NIKOLE HANNAH-JONES: So
magnets are complicated.

00:59:37.820 --> 00:59:40.270
So what magnet
schools are, they're

00:59:40.270 --> 00:59:43.010
traditional public schools,
but magnet programs

00:59:43.010 --> 00:59:45.220
started as a
desegregation program.

00:59:45.220 --> 00:59:47.860
And typically, magnet
schools were placed, like,

00:59:47.860 --> 00:59:49.960
within segregated
black communities.

00:59:49.960 --> 00:59:53.080
And then they would put
a really fabulous program

00:59:53.080 --> 00:59:55.480
in the schools, hoping
that they would then draw

00:59:55.480 --> 00:59:57.770
in white parents voluntarily.

00:59:57.770 --> 01:00:02.470
So my problem with it
is the whole premise

01:00:02.470 --> 01:00:04.270
is that if you
want white parents,

01:00:04.270 --> 01:00:06.250
you'd better create
something really good.

01:00:06.250 --> 01:00:08.620
And otherwise, you
know, they won't come.

01:00:08.620 --> 01:00:10.120
But what is that
saying about, like,

01:00:10.120 --> 01:00:11.578
the kids who are
in that community,

01:00:11.578 --> 01:00:13.880
and what they deserve?

01:00:13.880 --> 01:00:17.770
So I think, like,
fundamentally, I

01:00:17.770 --> 01:00:20.020
have a problem with the
way that we privilege

01:00:20.020 --> 01:00:23.560
white parents and the
message that it sends,

01:00:23.560 --> 01:00:26.860
but I also feel like,
this is really hard.

01:00:26.860 --> 01:00:29.440
And if you're trying
with a magnet school,

01:00:29.440 --> 01:00:34.680
I'm not going to put a
community down for doing that.

01:00:34.680 --> 01:00:36.670
But it's just not
a systemic answer.

01:00:36.670 --> 01:00:41.290
And a great example is
Hartford, Connecticut,

01:00:41.290 --> 01:00:46.360
which, because of a state
court order, had to integrate,

01:00:46.360 --> 01:00:50.670
and it created this
system of magnets

01:00:50.670 --> 01:00:52.900
to draw white kids
in from the suburbs.

01:00:52.900 --> 01:00:54.700
And the magnets are amazing.

01:00:54.700 --> 01:00:57.090
Like, there's one that has
a planetarium in there.

01:00:57.090 --> 01:01:00.550
Like, they spent millions
of dollars on these magnets

01:01:00.550 --> 01:01:03.880
to draw white kids in who had
a perfectly good education

01:01:03.880 --> 01:01:05.770
in their own backyards,
and were only coming

01:01:05.770 --> 01:01:08.020
because what they were able
to get through this magnet

01:01:08.020 --> 01:01:11.340
program in the city was better
than what they could get.

01:01:11.340 --> 01:01:13.870
But they were getting
good education anyway.

01:01:13.870 --> 01:01:18.220
And so half of the black kids in
Hartford can go to the magnet,

01:01:18.220 --> 01:01:20.860
and the other half of the
black kids get nothing.

01:01:20.860 --> 01:01:22.034
They don't get integration.

01:01:22.034 --> 01:01:23.200
They can't go to the magnet.

01:01:23.200 --> 01:01:24.880
Their schools are terrible.

01:01:24.880 --> 01:01:26.980
But in the name of
integration, this is the system

01:01:26.980 --> 01:01:28.030
that we've created.

01:01:28.030 --> 01:01:30.040
And they actually
denied black students.

01:01:30.040 --> 01:01:34.570
They hold seats empty to keep
a particular racial balance.

01:01:34.570 --> 01:01:36.994
So there's actually, in some
of the schools, empty seats,

01:01:36.994 --> 01:01:38.410
and the black kids
in the district

01:01:38.410 --> 01:01:41.300
can't go for racial balance.

01:01:41.300 --> 01:01:42.557
And that feels wrong to me.

01:01:42.557 --> 01:01:44.890
But I'm also like, they're
at least trying to integrate.

01:01:44.890 --> 01:01:48.270
And that's why I say,
like, there's just--

01:01:48.270 --> 01:01:51.106
this is being recorded,
so I shouldn't say this.

01:01:51.106 --> 01:01:53.240
And any time someone says
I shouldn't say this,

01:01:53.240 --> 01:01:55.670
and then they say
it's a bad idea.

01:01:55.670 --> 01:01:57.370
But the system is--

01:01:57.370 --> 01:02:01.381
the entire system is designed
to produce what it's producing.

01:02:01.381 --> 01:02:03.130
And that's what my
book is going to argue.

01:02:03.130 --> 01:02:04.380
Our schools are not broken.

01:02:04.380 --> 01:02:08.920
Our schools were designed
to favor white students

01:02:08.920 --> 01:02:10.760
and to provide black
and Latino students.

01:02:10.760 --> 01:02:12.759
And I mean, historically,
going all the way back

01:02:12.759 --> 01:02:14.500
to the creation
of public schools,

01:02:14.500 --> 01:02:17.770
to deny black and Latino
students an equal education.

01:02:17.770 --> 01:02:20.860
And so everything that we do
is functioning around that,

01:02:20.860 --> 01:02:25.604
that certain people have choice
and options, and others don't.

01:02:25.604 --> 01:02:27.520
But I think for you, I
mean, I don't want to--

01:02:27.520 --> 01:02:28.079
I don't know.

01:02:28.079 --> 01:02:29.120
Was it a good experience?

01:02:29.120 --> 01:02:30.310
AUDIENCE: Yeah, it
was a great school.

01:02:30.310 --> 01:02:31.434
NIKOLE HANNAH-JONES: Right.

01:02:31.434 --> 01:02:34.540
So I think for so
many white kids,

01:02:34.540 --> 01:02:37.421
our intentional integration
provided for them

01:02:37.421 --> 01:02:39.670
the opportunity to attend
integrated schools that they

01:02:39.670 --> 01:02:41.350
probably wouldn't have before.

01:02:41.350 --> 01:02:42.752
And I've heard from tons--

01:02:42.752 --> 01:02:44.710
I'm going to have a
chapter on this in my book,

01:02:44.710 --> 01:02:46.300
because I don't think we
talk enough to white kids who

01:02:46.300 --> 01:02:47.650
went to integrated schools.

01:02:47.650 --> 01:02:50.044
I think we always talk
about how it benefits

01:02:50.044 --> 01:02:51.460
black and brown
kids, and we never

01:02:51.460 --> 01:02:53.260
talk about how it
benefits white kids,

01:02:53.260 --> 01:02:55.280
and I think we need to
talk more about that.

01:02:55.280 --> 01:03:00.282
But I think overall, magnets
also replicate inequality,

01:03:00.282 --> 01:03:02.740
and that you're building these
fabulous schools just so you

01:03:02.740 --> 01:03:04.270
can get white kids in there.

01:03:04.270 --> 01:03:06.850
And then the black kids who are
already in that neighborhood

01:03:06.850 --> 01:03:09.917
deserve those kinds
of schools too.

01:03:09.917 --> 01:03:10.750
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

01:03:10.750 --> 01:03:12.042
NIKOLE HANNAH-JONES: Thank you.

01:03:12.042 --> 01:03:13.458
SHEETHAL SHOBAWALE:
Nikole, I want

01:03:13.458 --> 01:03:14.720
to thank you so much for this.

01:03:14.720 --> 01:03:16.636
I wish I could read your
book, like, tomorrow.

01:03:16.636 --> 01:03:18.240
NIKOLE HANNAH-JONES: I wish
it was written by tomorrow.

01:03:18.240 --> 01:03:18.850
SHEETHAL SHOBAWALE: I
can't wait till 2019.

01:03:18.850 --> 01:03:19.840
[LAUGHTER]

01:03:19.840 --> 01:03:20.380
No pressure.

01:03:20.380 --> 01:03:20.950
[APPLAUSE]

01:03:20.950 --> 01:03:23.050
But thank you so
much for being here.

01:03:23.050 --> 01:03:24.900
NIKOLE HANNAH-JONES: Thank you.

